<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="29818f8b6da266174ddd746571e9b090" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> The Judicator - Part 1 of 3<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.59)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=10058'>David "Lirkas 'DDM'" Destefanis</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=10058&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 26, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> <b><u>Introduction:</b></u><br />
<br />
This is an article about a Dark Side ship : the <i>Judicator</i>. It is divided in 4 chapters, and this part will be about the <u>first two</u>.<br />
First chapter will be analysis of the ship&#39;s statistic and comparing them with the other ISD the DS can play.<br />
Second chapter will be the focus of the strength of the Judicator.<br />
Third chapter will be an analysis on the support cards you can use for maximum effectiveness.<br />
Fourth chapter will be an overall opinion on how/when (also decktypes) to use the Judicator and eventual support cards. How is the ship considered in the overall meta and why. <br />
<br />
<i>Before starting, know that I personally think the Judicator to be one of the best Imperial Starships (mind, Imperial, Im not considering independent starships) ever created.<br />
Maybe the best example posted on DT is the following:</i><br />
<br />
Ferocious Domination (State Winning deck in 2003):<br />
http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/decks/decks.php?deck=29178<br />
<br />
<br />
<b><u>CHAPTER 1: Raw analysis</b></u><br />
<br />
<i>Note: I won&#39;t compare during my analysis the Judicator towards the Executor when speaking about statistics, since the Executor is a SSD, while the Judicator is an ISD.</i><br />
<br />
Let&#39;s look at the card text again:<br />
<b><u>Judicator</b></u><br />
Deploy 8, Forfeit 9, Destiny 1<br />
<u>Game text</u>: <i>May add 6 pilots, 8 passengers, 2 vehicles and 4 TIEs. Has ship-docking capability. Permanent pilot provides ability of 1. Each of its weapon destiny draws is +2. Starfighters it &#39;hits&#39; are power = 0.</i><br />
<br />
a) <u>ability:</u><br />
The Judicator has a permament pilot of ability 1 aboard. Pretty lame. I mean, even a stupid Imperial Pilot has more ability. :)<br />
This alone takes out the Judicator from any deck with few starships, since you can&#39;t put an ability 2 pilot on it to draw battle destiny. You need to add 3 ability to get to 4.<br />
Even in Big Blue decks, you would usually prefer other ISD that have either higher power, lower deploy or higher ability.<br />
<br />
b) <u>deploy:</u><br />
The deploy of the Judicator is average. Like any standard ISD. It&#39;s 8. Now, with the new ISD (V), that draws battle destiny on its own, one would really wonder why to play the Judicator, since the stats are the same.<br />
On the other hand, it costs a little less than the Chimaera, a pretty much famous ISD in Dark decks, thanks to Thrawn and its natural immunity.<br />
<br />
c) <u>forfeit:</u><br />
Again, it is the average 9. Most ISD have this value, but for the Chimaera, with a 10.<br />
Nothing outstanding here, especially considering that forfeit 9 or 10 is still big, so being 11 or 8 wouldn&#39;t change the overall value of any ISD (the story is different if about deploy).<br />
<br />
d) <u>destiny:</u><br />
Again, your average ISD: 1.<br />
Really, it&#39;s not even a pathetic 2 (like some ISD).<br />
<br />
e) <u>hyperspeed:</u><br />
still 3. Ok, it&#39;s a little better than ONE ISD: the Thunderflare (it has 2). But come on, the Thunderflare has better deploy and power.<br />
<br />
f) <u>immunity to attrition:</u><br />
plainly put: none. You can create it with support cards, but the same goes with any ISD. <br />
<br />
g) <u>specific game text:</u><br />
<i>Each of its weapon destiny draws is +2. Starfighters it &#39;hits&#39; are power = 0.</i><br />
The Judicator, being a less than average ISD, has to get a good game text to justify its use.<br />
However, while the Chimaera has a built-in immunity to attrition <4 (that can jump to <6) and ability 2, which helps in ANY deck (good overall game text), the Judicator has a game text about weapons, which means that without weapons this ISD is useless.<br />
The first part of the game text says:<br />
&quot;<i>Each of its weapon destiny draws is +2.</i>&quot;<br />
This means that the Judicator &#39;hits&#39; any ship easier than any other ISD. <br />
The second part of the game text says:<br />
<i>Starfighters it &#39;hits&#39; are power = 0. </i><br />
This means that this ISD is the bane of LS starfighters, since it drops their power to 0 with a successful &#39;hit&#39; (done easier than normal thanks to the +2 bonus), much like the dreaded LS interrupt Power Pivot (Dark Side counterpart: Relentless Pursuit).<br />
All in all, the Judicator&#39;s strengths come when armed with 1 or more weapons, where it shines. The only other ISD that has a game text for weapons is the Thunderflare (&quot;turbolaser batteries may deploy and fire for free&quot;), but, while strong, it is nowhere as strong as the Judicator.<br />
<br />
<br />
<u><b>CHAPTER 2:  Focus on the strengths of the Judicator</u></b><br />
<br />
We understood that the Judicators strengths are &quot;weapons&quot;.<br />
So the weapons, while technically &quot;support cards&quot; (and so should be considered in Part 3) have to be considered mainly here.<br />
<br />
The weapons of any ISD can be:<br />
<br />
<b>Ion Cannon<br />
Turbolaser Battery<br />
Heavy Turbolaser Battery<br />
Laser Cannon Battery</b><br />
<br />
Let&#39;s look at the weapons 1 by 1.<br />
<br />
<u>Ion Cannon (destiny 5)</u><br />
<i>Use 2 Force to deploy on your Star Destroyer. May target a starship using 1 Force. Draw destiny. If destiny +2 > defense value, all starship weapons deployed on target are<br />
lost, armor or maneuver = 0 and hyperspeed = 0.</i><br />
<br />
The ion cannon is the only weapon that does not use fully the Judicator&#39;s game text, since it does not &#39;hit&#39; anything (so no power=0 to starfighters). <br />
However, the Judicator would fire the Ion Cannon at +4, which is not bad at all (you need just a 3 to hit any maneuver 6 starfighter), especially considering that you might take out nasty LS weapons like Intruder Missiles or X-Wing Cannon (you do not risk anything against them, but Power Pivot could still be played), or even a Proton Torpedoes before an attack run.<br />
On the bad side, without any support cards, the Ion Cannon still costs 2 to deploy and 1 to fire (where every force counts, it is a little high, for a weapon that does not &#39;hit&#39; anything).<br />
It is, however, still destiny 5, which means that when floating through your deck, it still has its uses.<br />
<br />
<u>Turbolaser Battery</u> (destiny 2)<br />
<i>Use 3 Force to deploy on any Star Destroyer or any mobile system. May target a starship using 2 Force. Draw 2 destiny. Substract 2 if targeting a capital starship. Otherwise, subtract 5. Target hit if total destiny > defense value.</i><br />
<br />
The Premiere version of the Turbolaser Battery is maybe the lamest capital weapon created (it was indeed the first). It has a horrible destiny of 2, and without support cards, cost a huge 3 Force to deploy but mostly 2 Force to fire.<br />
The Turbolaser Battery, without the Judicator&#39;s help, wasn&#39;t likely to hit anything but LS capitals (to hit a maneuver 6 starfighter, you would need to draw two 6 for weapon destiny). Since most LS capitals have armor 4, the Turbolaser Battery needed only to draw 4+3 (or any total of 7) to hit them. Not so hard, albeit not a piece of cake either.<br />
With the Judicator, things change, since the +2 bonus apply to each weapon destiny.<br />
It means that you need you need a total of 8 to hit a maneuver 6 starfigther (average difficulty) but only a total of 3 (really easy on two weapon destiny) to hit a armor 4 capital.<br />
<br />
<u>Heavy Turbolaser Battery</u> (destiny 3)<br />
<i>Use 4 Force to deploy on your Star Destroyer (adds 2 to power) or any mobile system. May target a starship using 2 Force. Draw two destiny. Substract 1 when targeting a capital starship. Otherwise, substract 6. Target hit if total destiny > defense value.</i><br />
<br />
One would think the SE version of the Turbolaser Battery to be an improvement on its lame precedent version. It is not really and shouldn&#39;t be used but in the most focused Star Destroyer / weapons deck (you can find an example on the following link:<br />
http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/decks/decks.php?deck=28737<br />
The destiny is slightly better (3), but still low, and the cost to deploy is even higher (4).<br />
The overall weapon destiny to hit starships do not change much (with the Judicator, you need a 9 total to hit starfighters and a 2 total to hit capitals), but on the good side, it adds 2 to your Star Destroyer power.<br />
All in all, better than the Premiere version, but only because of destiny and +2 to power.<br />
<br />
<br />
<u>Laser Cannon Battery</u> (destiny 4)<br />
<i>Deploy on your capital starship. May deploy as a &#39;react&#39;. May target a starship using X Force, where X = 0 to 3. Draw destiny. Subtract 2 if targeting a starship with maneuver. If destiny +X > defense value, target hit and opponent loses 1 Force.</i><br />
<br />
This weapon, the most recent one (Coruscant expansion), is by far the most interesting capital weapon.<br />
The trend to put higher destiny with each new expansion is kept (2 to 3, then 3 to 4), and for the first time, it deploys for free.<br />
Looking at this weapon, there is nothing bad about it: you can fire for free also, but you can also boost the weapon destiny draw up to 3, akin to the Tie Interceptor Cannons. When you hit something, you do not make it immediately lost (like the T/I cannon) but you make the opponent lose 1 Force, which is always nice, and also you don&#39;t need to pay 3 Force to do it: any hit, even without boosting your weapon destiny draw, will do.<br />
Also, this weapon can deploy as a &#39;react&#39;. This is big, especially since it allows you to keep your weapon in hand and deploy it only if the opponent battles you (if you&#39;re defending more than one system), without relying on support cards to do it (like Heavy Fire Zone). The surprise factor is also to be considered.<br />
With the Judicator, it means that you are shooting from +2 to +5 vs. starships with armor (not only capitals, then, but also Radiant VII and the like), and from +0 to +3 vs. starships with maneuver.<br />
Overall, a pretty nice picture: capitals with armor 4 are hit automatically if you boost your weapon destiny draw and starfighters with maneuver 6 can be hit with a 4 only (exactly like the T/I cannon, which is a staple in many decks).<br />
To hit the Home One (the most armoured LS capital ship), you also need only a 4.<br />
<br />
<br />
All in all, the Laser Cannon Batteries are definitively the weapons to use.<br />
The strong point about the Judicator using these weapons is that you can pack more than one Laser Cannon Battery on it and shoot multiple times during a battle, EVEN if there is only one opposing ship present AND if it has already been hit. (you can hit multiple times a single starship for additional force loss)<br />
Every time you hit, you make the opponent lose 1 Force, and if it is a starfighter, it is power=0.<br />
This is akin to Lateral Damage, with the following difference:<br />
<u>Pro:</u><br />
- the starfighter iexhaust, so it must be forfeited at the end of the battle. Not the same with Lateral Damage, where someone could still forfeit something else and run to the system where the Utinni Effect is to cancel it.<br />
- you can have only 1 Lateral Damage on table. Which means only one ship will be power=0. Nothing prevents you, however, to pack multiple Laser Cannon Battery (up to 3 shots for a battle) and shoot multiple ships/times during a battle.<br />
- the Lateral Damage goes to the Lost Pile after use, not the Laser Cannon Battery.<br />
- ships can be immune to Lateral Damage (like Han, Chewie and the Falcon)<br />
<u>Con:</u><br />
- Lateral Damage gives the opponent&#39;s ship forfeit=0 (the weapon doesn&#39;t).<br />
- Lateral Damage is automatical (while with the weapon you have still to &#39;hit&#39;).<br />
<br />
Now, the power=0 part of the text works only if you hit a starfighter.<br />
But the meta, especially before V6, was totally not oriented towards Capital predominance in LS decks (now, with V6, it&#39;s a little different). The most you could see was from time to time a Home One (usually alone in the deck, or with Han, Chewie and the Falcon) and sometimes the Spiral. All the rest were starfighters. To name a few:<br />
<br />
Luke(V) with Artoo Detoo In Red 5<br />
Wedge Antilles, Red Squadron Leader, with Red Squadron 1<br />
Han, Chewie and the Falcon <br />
Dash Rendar with the Outrider<br />
<br />
And some outsiders, like Mirax with the Pulsar Skate, Ten Numb with Blue 5, etc.<br />
Without considering the swarm decks, made with X-Wings usually.<br />
So usually, when facing LS ships, they were mostly starfighters. So the Judicator is at ease with the LS fleet usually (especially after a few shooting). <br />
<br />
The Judicator has problems when facing swarms that run away, simply because it cannot be everywhere at once (a problem that every ISD faces) so having only 1 ISD, the Judicator, in your deck, wont make you destroy the LS fleet around the galaxy, but will give you a definite chance to hold a system.<br />
<br />
Putting faith in the well-known Chimaera with Thrawn (and Guri / Imperial Command) instead of the Judicator is a more all-around solution (since the Chimaera is a nice ISD without Thrawn, and Thrawn and Guri are useful on the ground too), but it is not foolfproof.<br />
There are many ways to bypass the Combo of Thrawn/Chimaera, like the LS winning a podrace and then placing Wedge Red Squadron Leader with another Red (or Rogue) Squadron pilot (usually Luke) at Malastare: the DS is not drawing more than 1 Battle Destiny, and this Battle Destiny is cancelled by Wedge.<br />
Playing Artoo, I Have A Bad Feeling About This (easy when playing with Artoo & Threepio) is another way, although less effective in the long run.<br />
<br />
The Judicator just punches through everything, since it relies on weapons destinies, and not battle destinies, to get the job done.<br />
Of course, there might be some problems to hit starfighters that pack A Few Maneuvers, since it would require you a 6 for weapon destiny, but you can do it with tracking. Also, A Few Maneuvers goes to the Used Pile while the Laser Cannon Battery stays on table (allowing you to hit another time next battle while the opponent will have to draw another interrupt to be safe).<br />
Also, some other DS cards exist to increase your chance to hit a starship, so you can meta for it. And at last, only 1 starfighter can be protected by A Few Maneuvers during battle, and a lone starfighter is not a threat to a fully operational Judicator (so other starfighters can be hit with your other Laser Cannon Batteries easily).<br />
Finally, the possibility to hit is the same as for the T/I Cannons, and no-one is complaining about them.<br />
<br />
Last bonus, making the opponent&#39;s starfighters power=0 means that by shooting the Outrider as soon as you can (first action in your battle phase, works usually only when you are attacking), you won&#39;t suffer any power reducing. Indeed the Outrider is easily hit so it is no more of a problem for the Dark Side.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
This is the end of part 1. Part 2 will deal with chapter 3, support cards. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php?id=5400&view=1&PHPSESSID=29818f8b6da266174ddd746571e9b090'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=29818f8b6da266174ddd746571e9b090'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/starwarsccg/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=29818f8b6da266174ddd746571e9b090'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table>
